<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-284-304  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 284 304.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  March 5 1990 n260 p28(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Changing trade winds. (US export policy lags)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pelton, Charles.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>US trade policy that deals with the transfer of high technologyequipment to East Bloc countries is in a state of flux.andP;  USvendors must get through a continual maze of regulations thathamper trade with countries that remain East Bloc.andP;  This resultsin a loss of business and costly delays for US companies.andP;  Firmsbased in countries with less stringent export control rules gainmarket share from US firms in these circumstances.andP;  Some type oflicense is required for any product or high technology export toany country other than Canada.andP;  The license must be obtained fromthe US Commerce Department's Office of Export Licensing.andP;  Hightechnology products that do not contribute to a military potentialor are not in short supply in the country of destiny can beshipped with a general license that is routinely available.andO;Sensitive technology must be shipped with a validated license thatsometimes requires approval by the Department of Defense.andP;  Inaddition, a unanimous approval is sometimes required from theCoordinating Committee for Military Export Control (Cocom).andP;  Cocomis a Paris based organization for regulation of sensitivetechnology imports to Warsaw Pact countries.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     International TradeForeign CompetitionTechnology TransferEuropeGovernment RegulationExportPolitical IssuesChinaUnited States. Department of Commerce.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>